---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-malaysia', text: 'Leaving Malaysian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'epf-considerations', text: 'EPF Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Singaporean Expat Insurance', href: '/best/singaporean-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Gulf Region Insurance', href: '/best/gulf-region-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'asiaNetwork', header: 'Asia Network' },
  { key: 'globalNetwork', header: 'Global Network' },
  { key: 'malaysiaCoverage', header: 'Malaysia Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', asiaNetwork: 'Strong', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', malaysiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'RM 750/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', asiaNetwork: 'Excellent', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', malaysiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'RM 850/mo' },
  { provider: 'AIA Malaysia', asiaNetwork: 'Good', globalNetwork: 'Good', malaysiaCoverage: 'Included', price: 'RM 600/mo' },
  { provider: 'Great Eastern Malaysia', asiaNetwork: 'Good', globalNetwork: 'Limited', malaysiaCoverage: 'Included', price: 'RM 550/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', asiaNetwork: 'Good', globalNetwork: 'Strong', malaysiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'RM 700/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Malaysian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Malaysian expats. Find coverage for Singapore, Australia, UK, and other destinations while understanding EPF implications."
  headline="Best Insurance for Malaysian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Malaysia has excellent healthcare, but it doesn't follow you abroad. Here's how to stay covered while understanding your EPF options."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/malaysian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Malaysian expats are found in Singapore, Australia, UK, US, and other countries. Understanding how Malaysian healthcare and EPF work abroad is important. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Malaysian expats. Strong networks worldwide, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. Top-tier service quality.</li>
    <li><strong>AIA Malaysia:</strong> Major Malaysian insurer with international products. Familiar brand, includes Malaysia.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices.</li>
    <li><strong>Great Eastern Malaysia:</strong> Malaysian insurer with some international options. Familiar service.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Singapore Consideration"
    description="Singapore is the most common destination for Malaysian expats. While Singapore healthcare is excellent, it's also expensive. Work pass holders have some coverage requirements, but comprehensive international insurance provides better protection."
    buttonText="Compare Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-malaysia">Leaving Malaysian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Malaysia has a dual public-private healthcare system. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>Public Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    Malaysian public healthcare is available to citizens at subsidized rates. However, this only works in Malaysia—there's no international coverage. Moving abroad means you need independent insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Malaysian Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private health insurance from Malaysian companies (AIA, Great Eastern, Prudential Malaysia) typically provides limited international coverage—usually emergency treatment abroad for short periods. Long-term stays overseas need dedicated international insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>SOCSO (PERKESO)</h3>
  <p>
    SOCSO provides employment injury and invalidity coverage for Malaysian workers. It doesn't provide general health insurance and doesn't extend internationally.
  </p>

  <h3>Medical and Health Insurance Scheme</h3>
  <p>
    The government's health insurance schemes cover eligible persons but only within Malaysia. International coverage requires separate insurance.
  </p>

  <h2 id="epf-considerations">EPF Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    The Employees Provident Fund (EPF/KWSP) is important for Malaysian financial planning:
  </p>

  <h3>EPF Contributions Abroad</h3>
  <p>
    When working abroad, you're not required to contribute to EPF. However, you can make voluntary contributions to maintain your retirement savings. EPF doesn't include healthcare coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>EPF Withdrawal</h3>
  <p>
    Permanent emigration allows EPF withdrawal under certain conditions. Consider the implications carefully—once withdrawn, you lose the retirement savings mechanism.
  </p>

  <h3>Account II Withdrawals</h3>
  <p>
    Account II allows withdrawals for certain purposes including healthcare. However, this is for Malaysian healthcare—not international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Return Planning</h3>
  <p>
    If you plan to return to Malaysia, maintaining some EPF balance provides retirement security. Healthcare abroad requires separate international insurance regardless.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Healthcare Quality Expectations</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Malaysia has excellent private healthcare. International insurance should provide access to quality hospitals abroad matching your expectations. Don't compromise on coverage quality.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Malaysian expats. Strong networks in Singapore (most common destination), Australia, UK, and worldwide. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 English service, direct billing at major hospitals. Malaysia coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Malaysian expats who want reliable global coverage with strong networks.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent worldwide networks. Service quality is outstanding with comprehensive benefits including mental health and wellness.
  </p>

  <p>
    Higher pricing reflects premium quality. Malaysia coverage available as an add-on.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Malaysian professionals who want the best coverage available.
  </p>

  <h3>AIA Malaysia</h3>
  <p>
    AIA is one of Malaysia's major insurers and offers international products for Malaysians abroad. Familiar brand, familiar processes, Malaysia coverage included automatically.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are adequate, strongest in Asia-Pacific.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Malaysian expats who prefer familiar Malaysian service with seamless home coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks in Europe and adequate coverage elsewhere. Good value for comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Malaysian expats seeking good value with global coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Great Eastern Malaysia</h3>
  <p>
    Great Eastern is a major Malaysian insurer offering some international products. Familiar brand, Malaysia coverage included. International networks are more limited than global specialists.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Malaysian expats who prefer familiar Malaysian service and primarily need Malaysia coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Malaysian and International Options"
    description="Malaysian insurers offer familiar service; international insurers have broader global networks. Consider your destination when choosing."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Malaysian expats should consider:
  </p>

  <h3>Singapore</h3>
  <p>
    Most common Malaysian expat destination. Excellent healthcare but expensive. Work pass holders have coverage requirements. Many Malaysians commute or live in JB while working in Singapore. Comprehensive insurance ensures proper coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Australia</h3>
  <p>
    Significant Malaysian community, especially in Melbourne and Sydney. Medicare covers permanent residents after waiting period. International insurance covers the gap and supplements public healthcare.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    NHS provides free healthcare to legal residents with proper visa status. Many Malaysian expats supplement NHS with private insurance for faster access.
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    Growing Malaysian community. US healthcare is extremely expensive—comprehensive coverage is essential. Don't underestimate costs.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does Malaysian insurance cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Malaysian insurance provides limited international coverage (emergency only, short periods). For living abroad, you need dedicated international health insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I use EPF for healthcare abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">EPF Account II allows healthcare withdrawals, but only for Malaysian healthcare. International medical expenses need separate insurance coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about working in Singapore?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Singapore work pass holders have some coverage requirements. Comprehensive international insurance provides better protection and choice than minimum requirements.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during Malaysia visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">AIA Malaysia and Great Eastern include Malaysia automatically. International insurers offer Malaysia as a coverage region.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is AIA or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">AIA offers Malaysian familiarity and includes Malaysia. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on destination and service preferences.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Should I withdraw EPF when emigrating?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Consider carefully. Withdrawal provides immediate funds but ends retirement savings. Many Malaysians maintain EPF even while abroad. Healthcare requires separate insurance regardless.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Malaysian expats need comprehensive international insurance—Malaysian healthcare doesn't work abroad. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for reliable coverage with strong networks, especially in Singapore.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who can afford the best. <strong>AIA Malaysia</strong> suits those who prefer familiar Malaysian service with included home coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    EPF is for retirement, not international healthcare. Maintain appropriate international insurance regardless of your EPF decisions.
  </p>

</PageShell>
